Here's a step-by-step guide to integrate Plugin Update Checker (PUC) with GitHub so your users can receive plugin updates directly in the WordPress admin panel.

✅ Step-by-Step Setup for Plugin Update Checker (GitHub)
🔧 1. Prepare Your Plugin Repository on GitHub
Create a public GitHub repository (private also works with an access token, but public is simpler).

Structure your plugin folder like this:

cpp
Copy
Edit
your-plugin/
├── your-plugin.php
├── readme.txt (optional)
└── plugin-update-checker/ (PUC library will go here)
Inside your main plugin file (e.g. your-plugin.php), make sure to define:

php
Copy
Edit
/*
Plugin Name: Your Plugin Name
Version: 1.0.0
*/

📁 2. Add the Plugin Update Checker Library
Download from GitHub:
https://github.com/YahnisElsts/plugin-update-checker

Place the entire plugin-update-checker folder inside your plugin.

🧩 3. Add the Update Checker Code
Add this near the top of your main plugin file (your-plugin.php):

php
Copy
Edit
require plugin_dir_path(__FILE__) . 'plugin-update-checker/plugin-update-checker.php';

$myUpdateChecker = Puc_v4_Factory::buildUpdateChecker(
    'https://github.com/your-username/your-plugin-repo/',
    __FILE__,
    'your-plugin-slug'
);
🔁 Replace:

'your-username/your-plugin-repo' with your actual GitHub username/repo

'your-plugin-slug' with your plugin's slug (folder name)

🏷️ 4. Tag Releases in GitHub
To trigger updates:

Commit all plugin files to your GitHub repo

Go to GitHub > Releases → Create a new release

Use the tag like v1.0.1 (must match version in your plugin header)

Upload the ZIP if you want (optional)

✅ Now, whenever you update the plugin:

Change the Version: in your plugin file

Create a new GitHub release with a matching tag

🔐 Optional: Use GitHub Access Token (for private repo)
If your repo is private, generate a GitHub Personal Access Token (with repo scope) and add this after the checker:

php
Copy
Edit
$myUpdateChecker->setAuthentication('your_github_token');

🧪 5. Test the Update
Install the plugin on a test site from ZIP or GitHub clone

When a new version is tagged on GitHub:

It will appear in Dashboard > Updates and Plugins page

You can update it like any other plugin

🧼 Example Folder Structure
sql
Copy
Edit
your-plugin/
├── plugin-update-checker/
├── your-plugin.php
└── ...
✅ Bonus: Add Changelog (Optional)
You can use GitHub release description to show changelog in the plugin update modal.
